100: /**
101:  * A Kafka client that publishes records to the Kafka cluster.
102:  * <P>
103:  * The producer is <i>thread safe</i> and sharing a single producer instance across threads will generally be faster than
104:  * having multiple instances.
105:  * <p>
106:  * Here is a simple example of using the producer to send records with strings containing sequential numbers as the key/value
107:  * pairs.
108:  * <pre>
109:  * {@code
110:  * Properties props = new Properties();
111:  * props.put("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");
112:  * props.put("linger.ms", 1);
113:  * props.put("key.serializer", "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer");
114:  * props.put("value.serializer", "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer");
115:  *
116:  * Producer<String, String> producer = new KafkaProducer<>(props);
117:  * for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
118:  *     producer.send(new ProducerRecord<String, String>("my-topic", Integer.toString(i), Integer.toString(i)));
119:  *
120:  * producer.close();
121:  * }</pre>
122:  * <p>
123:  * The producer consists of a pool of buffer space that holds records that haven't yet been transmitted to the server
124:  * as well as a background I/O thread that is responsible for turning these records into requests and transmitting them
125:  * to the cluster. Failure to close the producer after use will leak these resources.
126:  * <p>
127:  * The {@link #send(ProducerRecord) send()} method is asynchronous. When called, it adds the record to a buffer of pending record sends
128:  * and immediately returns. This allows the producer to batch together individual records for efficiency.
129:  * <p>
130:  * The <code>acks</code> config controls the criteria under which requests are considered complete. The default setting "all"
131:  * will result in blocking on the full commit of the record, the slowest but most durable setting.
132:  * <p>
133:  * If the request fails, the producer can automatically retry. The <code>retries</code> setting defaults to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>, and
134:  * it's recommended to use <code>delivery.timeout.ms</code> to control retry behavior, instead of <code>retries</code>.
135:  * <p>
136:  * The producer maintains buffers of unsent records for each partition. These buffers are of a size specified by
137:  * the <code>batch.size</code> config. Making this larger can result in more batching, but requires more memory (since we will
138:  * generally have one of these buffers for each active partition).
139:  * <p>
140:  * By default a buffer is available to send immediately even if there is additional unused space in the buffer. However if you
141:  * want to reduce the number of requests you can set <code>linger.ms</code> to something greater than 0. This will
142:  * instruct the producer to wait up to that number of milliseconds before sending a request in hope that more records will
143:  * arrive to fill up the same batch. This is analogous to Nagle's algorithm in TCP. For example, in the code snippet above,
144:  * likely all 100 records would be sent in a single request since we set our linger time to 1 millisecond. However this setting
145:  * would add 1 millisecond of latency to our request waiting for more records to arrive if we didn't fill up the buffer. Note that
146:  * records that arrive close together in time will generally batch together even with <code>linger.ms=0</code>. So, under heavy load,
147:  * batching will occur regardless of the linger configuration; however setting this to something larger than 0 can lead to fewer, more
148:  * efficient requests when not under maximal load at the cost of a small amount of latency.
149:  * <p>
150:  * The <code>buffer.memory</code> controls the total amount of memory available to the producer for buffering. If records
151:  * are sent faster than they can be transmitted to the server then this buffer space will be exhausted. When the buffer space is
152:  * exhausted additional send calls will block. The threshold for time to block is determined by <code>max.block.ms</code> after which it returns
153:  * a failed future with BufferExhaustedException.
154:  * <p>
155:  * The <code>key.serializer</code> and <code>value.serializer</code> instruct how to turn the key and value objects the user provides with
156:  * their <code>ProducerRecord</code> into bytes. You can use the included {@link org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.ByteArraySerializer} or
157:  * {@link org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer} for simple byte or string types.
158:  * <p>
159:  * From Kafka 0.11, the KafkaProducer supports two additional modes: the idempotent producer and the transactional producer.
160:  * The idempotent producer strengthens Kafka's delivery semantics from at least once to exactly once delivery. In particular
161:  * producer retries will no longer introduce duplicates. The transactional producer allows an application to send messages
162:  * to multiple partitions (and topics!) atomically.
163:  * </p>
164:  * <p>
165:  * From Kafka 3.0, the <code>enable.idempotence</code> configuration defaults to true. When enabling idempotence,
166:  * <code>retries</code> config will default to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> and the <code>acks</code> config will
167:  * default to <code>all</code>. There are no API changes for the idempotent producer, so existing applications will
168:  * not need to be modified to take advantage of this feature.
169:  * </p>
170:  * <p>
171:  * To take advantage of the idempotent producer, it is imperative to avoid application level re-sends since these cannot
172:  * be de-duplicated. As such, if an application enables idempotence, it is recommended to leave the <code>retries</code>
173:  * config unset, as it will be defaulted to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>. Additionally, if a {@link #send(ProducerRecord)}
174:  * returns an error even with infinite retries (for instance if the message expires in the buffer before being sent),
175:  * then it is recommended to shut down the producer and check the contents of the last produced message to ensure that
176:  * it is not duplicated. Finally, the producer can only guarantee idempotence for messages sent within a single session.
177:  * </p>
178:  * <p>To use the transactional producer and the attendant APIs, you must set the <code>transactional.id</code>
179:  * configuration property. If the <code>transactional.id</code> is set, idempotence is automatically enabled along with
180:  * the producer configs which idempotence depends on. Further, topics which are included in transactions should be configured
181:  * for durability. In particular, the <code>replication.factor</code> should be at least <code>3</code>, and the
182:  * <code>min.insync.replicas</code> for these topics should be set to 2. Finally, in order for transactional guarantees
183:  * to be realized from end-to-end, the consumers must be configured to read only committed messages as well.
184:  * </p>
185:  * <p>
186:  * The purpose of the <code>transactional.id</code> is to enable transaction recovery across multiple sessions of a
187:  * single producer instance. It would typically be derived from the shard identifier in a partitioned, stateful, application.
188:  * As such, it should be unique to each producer instance running within a partitioned application.
189:  * </p>
190:  * <p>All the new transactional APIs are blocking and will throw exceptions on failure. The example
191:  * below illustrates how the new APIs are meant to be used. It is similar to the example above, except that all
192:  * 100 messages are part of a single transaction.
193:  * </p>
194:  * <p>
195:  * <pre>
196:  * {@code
197:  * Properties props = new Properties();
198:  * props.put("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");
199:  * props.put("transactional.id", "my-transactional-id");
200:  * Producer<String, String> producer = new KafkaProducer<>(props, new StringSerializer(), new StringSerializer());
201:  *
202:  * producer.initTransactions();
203:  *
204:  * try {
205:  *     producer.beginTransaction();
206:  *     for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
207:  *         producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("my-topic", Integer.toString(i), Integer.toString(i)));
208:  *     producer.commitTransaction();
209:  * } catch (ProducerFencedException | OutOfOrderSequenceException | AuthorizationException e) {
210:  *     // We can't recover from these exceptions, so our only option is to close the producer and exit.
211:  *     producer.close();
212:  * } catch (KafkaException e) {
213:  *     // For all other exceptions, just abort the transaction and try again.
214:  *     producer.abortTransaction();
215:  * }
216:  * producer.close();
217:  * } </pre>
218:  * </p>
219:  * <p>
220:  * As is hinted at in the example, there can be only one open transaction per producer. All messages sent between the
221:  * {@link #beginTransaction()} and {@link #commitTransaction()} calls will be part of a single transaction. When the
222:  * <code>transactional.id</code> is specified, all messages sent by the producer must be part of a transaction.
223:  * </p>
224:  * <p>
225:  * The transactional producer uses exceptions to communicate error states. In particular, it is not required
226:  * to specify callbacks for <code>producer.send()</code> or to call <code>.get()</code> on the returned Future: a
227:  * <code>KafkaException</code> would be thrown if any of the
228:  * <code>producer.send()</code> or transactional calls hit an irrecoverable error during a transaction. See the {@link #send(ProducerRecord)}
229:  * documentation for more details about detecting errors from a transactional send.
230:  * </p>
231:  * </p>By calling
232:  * <code>producer.abortTransaction()</code> upon receiving a <code>KafkaException</code> we can ensure that any
233:  * successful writes are marked as aborted, hence keeping the transactional guarantees.
234:  * </p>
235:  * <p>
236:  * This client can communicate with brokers that are version 0.10.0 or newer. Older or newer brokers may not support
237:  * certain client features.  For instance, the transactional APIs need broker versions 0.11.0 or later. You will receive an
238:  * <code>UnsupportedVersionException</code> when invoking an API that is not available in the running broker version.
239:  * </p>
240:  */
